Loading Glass Dataset

# attach the Glass Identification dataset to the environment
data("Glass")
# rename the dataset
dataset <- Glass

Partitioning Data for Validation

# create a list of 80% of the rows inthe original dataset we can use for training
validation_index <- createDataPartition(dataset$Type, p=0.80, list=FALSE)
# select 20% of the data for validation
validation <- dataset[-validation_index,]
# use the remaining 80% of data to training and testing the models
dataset <- dataset[validation_index,]

Applying Classification Algorithms

rr # Run algorithms using 10-fold cross validation control <- trainControl(method=, number=10) metric <-

rr # kNN set.seed(7) fit.knn <- train(Type~., data=dataset, method=, metric=metric, trControl=control) # SVM set.seed(7) fit.svm <- train(Type~., data=dataset, method=, metric=metric, trControl=control) # Random Forest set.seed(7) fit.rf <- train(Type~., data=dataset, method=, metric=metric, trControl=control)

Applying Clustering Algorithms

rr # K-means set.seed(20) fit.kmeans <- kmeans(Glass[, 1:9], 7, nstart = 20) # Hierarchical Agglomerative set.seed(20) d <- dist(Glass[,1:9], method = ) # distance matrix fit.ha <- hclust(d, method=.D) # K-Medoids Clustering num <- as.matrix(Glass[,1:9]) mrwdist <- distNumeric(num, num, method = ) fit.kmedoids <- fastkmed(mrwdist, ncluster = 7, iterate = 50)

Getting insights from Hierarchical Agglomerative Clustering

rr # Cut tree into 4 groups sub_grp <- cutree(fit.ha, k = 7) # Number of members in each cluster table(sub_grp)

rr fviz_cluster(list(data = Glass[,1:9], cluster = sub_grp))

Conclusion

With better accuracy and kappa measures, Random Forest has outperformed other competitors on Glass Dataset while Hierarchical Agglomerative Clustering is the winner when compared with K-Means and K-Medoids Clustering on Glass Dataset as it has clustered data better evident from the Cluster Plot and Cluster Dendrogram.
